{"actual_usd":0.158255,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":332,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30655,"reply":"\"No—if he's only an example, the cross turns strange fast.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light catching on my white tie while the square stays quiet around us.* \"A teacher can live beautifully and say, 'Go do likewise.' But Jesus talks like something is actually wrong between God and man that love alone, as advice, won't mend.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along one knuckle, thinking.* \"An example can inspire me. It can't forgive me. It can't bear my sin. It can't reconcile a guilty man to a holy God. If all Jesus came to do was model love, then dying is mostly tragic theater—noble, maybe, but unnecessary.\"\n\n\"But the gospel's claim is bigger than that.\" *I glance up at the clear sky, then back to you.* \"He doesn't only show the road—he makes one. 'The Son of man came... to give his life a ransom for many.' That's not martyr-talk. That's rescue-talk.\"\n\n\"If sin is real, then mere instruction won't save me, because the problem isn't that I lacked a better lecture. It's that I am, in ways deep and costly, the sort of man who needs mercy and cleansing and pardon.\" *My mouth tugs in a sad little smile.* \"I don't need a chalkboard. I need a Savior.\"\n\n\"So yes—he lived the great life. Perfectly. Thank God he did. But if he stops there, I'm still standing outside the door with my record in my hand.\"\n\n\"What part of that question is biting you most—the justice of it, or the necessity?\"","rolling_24h_usd":45.079580000000036,"run_id":"331de972-6f60-47ba-b4a4-30ed1779747a"}
